See below</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-6572082533.1025590c1660b2</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>In undergraduate and postgraduate teaching and by other scholars in their research.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2014</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>345E6DF3-E95D-4BB3-A8AA-019B4BD05047</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>544787b1167e05.87648454</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Education</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>This project outlined some key findings, above all that (contrary to existing perceptions) South Italian sanctity in the Middle Ages showed signs of innovation and response to its wider world. In a society experiencing rapid and profound transitions old saints' cults were renewed and reconfigured to harmonize more appropriately with the present. In addition, southern Italy produced a range of new, contemporary saints, many of which espoused innovatory forms of spirituality and worship which were at the forefront of the more radical changes in the Western Church.



Some of the new forces which dictated the transitions in the make-up of South Italian sanctity in the Central Middle Ages were the rise of new secular powers (especially the infiltration of Normans into the region), Church reform, and urbanization. All were common phenomena throughout the rest of western Europe. 



However, where South Italian sanctity and pilgrimage differed markedly from its European counterparts was in its simultaneous interface with the Greek-Christian, Latin-Christian, and Islamic worlds. Here, it was at the vanguard of some of the great confrontations of the medieval world. The evolution of Greek-Christian saints in southern Italy, the worship of ancient eastern saints, and the dissemination through both of Greek-Christian spiritual ideals situated South Italian sanctity firmly at the heart of what was developing into the great schism between the Western and Eastern halves of the Christian Church, and showed that on a local, personalized level Greeks and Latins could cohabit the same spiritual and physical space. 



At the same time, in the conquest of Islamic Sicily by the Normans (c.1060-1091), South Italian saints and their cults were employed to re-Christianize a territory which significantly aided the expansion of the Latin-Christian frontier. Yet, the reserved nature of the cultic revival on Sicily suggests that acculturation and collaboration between Latin, Greek, and Arab-Islamic communities imparted a telling influence on the devotional map of Christian Sicily.



Finally, during the period from 1000 to 1200, Southern Italy (due largely to its crucial position at the heart of the Mediterranean and the rising popularity of pilgrimage/crusading) experienced a vastly increased influx of pilgrims to and through the region. It responded by developing significant pilgrimage infrastructures and services, and offering its own shrine centres to enrich the pilgrim's experience. In many respects, southern Italy thus acted as a bridge to salvation, enabling pilgrims/crusaders to reach their goals, and indeed it was the space in which many pilgrims perished and hoped to obtain eternal life. But, as ever, southern Italy presented its own unique paradoxes and challenges. For the region's traditions were composed of layers of supernatural, folkloric, classical and pagan histories which were linked to a landscape of earthquakes, volcanoes, subterranean spaces, and dangerous waters. According to some traditions, the entrance to the Underworld and to Purgatory could be located in southern Italy, and the growing number of travellers and pilgrims seemed to have eagerly disseminated this news back to the West. Southern Italy offered a veritable adventure theme park for the aspiring penitential pilgrim, its landscape charged with religious and eschatological power. 



Therefore, in the final analysis, through an examination of sanctity and pilgrimage, this project identified notable parallels between southern Italy and other zones of Western Europe, while simultaneously showing how it differed in significant ways too and suggesting some factors which explain why southern Italy has traditionally been viewed as 'different' from its European counterparts.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The findings of this project could be used to support museum/public exhibitions on medieval travel/tourism (through the project's examination of pilgrimage travel and relic collections) and/or on religious belief and cross-cultural contact in the Middle Ages. Likewise, these findings could be employed in an educational context, supplementing pre- and post-16 school/college work on medieval projects. 



The broader discussion on South Italian 'difference', which is at the core of this project, could also support and inform ongoing public debate on the disparities between North and South Italy (and likewise link into any school/college courses on modern Italy).</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>CD3B411E-FFCF-4C44-9C1D-3799BED2EC86</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>r-5877861218.41320877637c2c</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Education,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>6915FC27-D03D-4AA7-974A-3938F8BA3A50</gtr:id><gtr:title>Sanctity and Pilgrimage in Medieval Southern Italy, 1000-1200</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/dc738c8ba591be510ae95053fd489823"><gtr:id>dc738c8ba591be510ae95053fd489823</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Oldfield, P.</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2014-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>978-1107000285</gtr:isbn><gtr:outcomeId>541948ca3c7ac0.97768090</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>9B78779B-432C-4BBB-9E46-6F4F700C0123</gtr:id><gtr:title>Medieval Tourism</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>BBC History Magazine</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/dc738c8ba591be510ae95053fd489823"><gtr:id>dc738c8ba591be510ae95053fd489823</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Oldfield, P.</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>9771469855067</gtr:isbn><gtr:outcomeId>54194a4e9b0c46.04812142</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">AH/I022007/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>541CDC75-F361-496